 professional-managerial class. Applying the methodologies of periodical studies and the theoretical concerns of masculinity studies, this book recontextualizes the prose and fiction of these authors by analyzing them in the material context of the magazine. Relating each author’s articulation of masculinity to the advertisements, editorials, and articles published in each issue, Leading with the Chin shows that Esquire reflected and helped to shape the forces that structured American masculinity in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMasculinity in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican literature.  aEsquire.  aadvertising.  amagazines.  amanhood.  amanliness.  amasculinities.  amasculinity.  amaterial culture.  aperiodicals.  apopular culture.  apostmodernism.  aprint culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751595940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487515959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487515959.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles